    "body": "The problem is in your code `update-downloaded` event will fire `autoUpdater.quitAndInstall();` after 5 seconds. Instead you can use IPC to notify your user of what is going on and let them have control when to update.\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nautoUpdater.on('update-downloaded', function(event, releaseNotes, releaseName) {\r\n      win.webContents.send('update-ready', releaseName);\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis will fire the `update-ready` event in your renderer. You can then make it alert them about an update. \r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nipc.on('update-ready', function (event, version) {\r\n      // Make notification appear\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen you can have a button talk back to the main process when you are ready to update.\r\n```javascript\r\nipc.send('update-apply');\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen in the main process you look for the event and call for the app to restart and apply the update.\r\n```javascript\r\nipc.on('update-apply', function (event) {\r\n      autoUpdater.quitAndInstall();\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nYou can do the same with the `checking-for-update`, `update-available`, `update-not-available`, `update-download`, and `error` events as well. And instead of calling `autoUpdater.checkForUpdates();` immediately you can have a button from your renderer do an IPC call to the main to call it. When you get really into it all you go from a silent style updater to one that is actually pretty customizable. So while it is kind of frustrating with the minimal example the design of it all is necessary to have a really flexible updater."
